<section class="page-container section-spacer" data-orb="3,4">
  <div class="geo-divider">
    <span class="geo-circle" style="background: var(--color-geo-blue);"></span>
    <span class="geo-circle" style="background: var(--color-geo-teal);"></span>
    <span class="geo-circle" style="background: var(--color-geo-coral);"></span>
  </div>
  <div style="display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: clamp(4rem, 8vw, 6rem); align-items: start;">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow fade-in">story</p>
      <h2 class="fade-in-up delay-1">From one brain to many.</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="fade-in-up delay-2">
      <p class="body-large" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">elly started as a personal tool. I have ADHD. Every productivity app I tried eventually made me feel worse, streak-shaming, feature bloat, subscription fatigue. So I built the thing I actually needed.</p>
      <p class="body-large" style="margin-bottom: 1.5rem;">A notes app that doesn't judge. A calendar that makes time visible. An AI assistant that creates things instead of just chatting about them. A habits tracker where missing a day doesn't destroy weeks of progress.</p>
      <p class="body-large" style="margin-bottom: 2rem;">It's self-hosted because your brain data shouldn't live on someone else's server. The backend is <a href="https://github.com/Kxetch/elly-server" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">open source</a>, so you don't have to take that claim on faith. And it's encrypted because privacy isn't a feature, it's a prerequisite.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
